<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Ministry Deports 3 Turkish Kurds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303124294 Paris AFP in English 1219 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2303124294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Annecy, France, March 23 (AFP) -- France has 
deported three Turkish Kurds after refusing them political 
asylum, local authorities in Annecy said Wednesday [23 March]. 
  Vural Seker, 22, Iman Seker and Semsettin Yildirim, 31, who 
entered France in 1989, were arrested on Monday when they 
reported to the local police station after the Interior Ministry 
rejected their asylum request. They were put on a plane for 
Istanbul on Tuesday. 
  The committee for the right of aslyum in Annecy condemned 
the 
deportations as "a veritable denial of human rights" and said 
the Kurds had been imprisoned and persecuted in Turkey. 
  But local authority spokeswoman Patricia Mauroy-Willaert 
defended the decision, saying the Kurds were "potential illegal 
immigrants" and that if they had been informed of the decision 
in advance they would have disappeared. 
  The Kurds' initial asylum request had been rejected and the 
refusal was confirmed on appeal. 

</TEXT>

