<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Students Block Trains To Protest Pay Cut Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303170894 Paris AFP in English 1635 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2303170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 23 (AFP) -- Striking students overran 
the tracks at a mainline station here Wednesday [23 March], 
blocking high-speed trains and suburban services. 
  Students protesting a government scheme to allow firms to 
pay 
less than the legal minimum wage to young people also occupied 
the railway station at Calais, northern France, for three hours, 
causing serious disruption. 
  In Lyon, eastern France, scene of violent demonstrations 
Monday and Tuesday, riot police used water cannon and fired tear 
gas to disperse a group of about 100 youths and tried to arrest 
another group armed with baseball bats. 
  Lyon students said most of them were holding meetings to 
plan 
for major country-wide demonstrations Friday. 
  In Paris, students in technical universities called a 
one-day 
strike. About 100 youths laid down on the tracks at 
Montparnasse station, holding up high-speed (TGV) trains and 
main-line expresses for two hours. Suburban services came to a 
halt. 
  In Calais, the state railway company SNCF bussed stranded 
passengers to other railway stations. 
  In Caen, Normandy, 1,000 students marched peacefully through 
the town before heading for the capital, where they held up 
trains for 30 minutes. Another group took over a nearby 
motorway tollgate, allowing drivers through against a token 
payment. Demonstrations were also reported at La Rochelle in 
the west and at Reims in the northeast. 
  Students are demanding complete withdrawal of the 
government's pay cut plan. 
  In its latest form, the plan states that young people with 
diplomas or university degrees may be paid 80 percent of an 
ordinary salary for 80 percent of working time, with 20 percent 
of training. 
  Initially, the government's scheme proposed that all youths 
be paid 20 percent less than the minimum wage of 5,900 francs 
(1,000 dollars) a month. Now only unqualified youths may be 
paid less than the minimum. 
  Students called the plan a poor reward for years of study 
and 
trade unionists denounced it as opening the way to firing older 
workers and replacing them with poorly paid youths. 
  France has 3.3 million unemployed -- almost 12 percent of 
the 
work force -- of whom more than 750,000 are under 25. 

</TEXT>

