<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Economic Forecasts for 1994 Show Buoyancy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94EN0241A Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT in Finnish 17 Feb 94 p 
B 1 </F>

<F P=103> 94EN0241A </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Johanna Korhonen: "Finnish Growth Tops Among </F>
Western Countries"] 
  [Excerpts] Finland's production will increase faster next 
year than in any other Western country. Unemployment will, 
however, remain at peak levels at the same time. 
  On Wednesday [16 February] the Finance Ministry published a 
forecast that claims Finland is climbing out of the recession. 
The recovery is, however, very unevenly distributed: Industrial 
production and exports will continue their vigorous growth, but, 
at the same time, domestic consumer spending will continue to 
decrease while unemployment will increase. 
  "The economy stabilized during last year, and the turn 
toward 
growth is now under way. This does not mean that the recession 
is over, however. The situation in some spheres of the domestic 
markets will get even worse," says Sixten Korkman, director of 
the Finance Ministry's Department of National Economy, as he 
presented the forecast. 
  The price competitiveness of Finnish industry is so good at 
the moment that exports this year are more than one-tenth higher 
than last year. The Finance Ministry is also predicting that 
demand for imports from Finland's most important trade partners 
will begin to rise and that export prices will increase by about 
6 percent. 
  The outward condition of the national economy will improve 
remarkably this year when the balance of trade, which measures 
the difference between currency gains and losses in foreign 
trade, will rise to a surplus as high as 12 billion markkas. 
  Last year, Finland's net foreign debt rose by 37 billion 
markkas, to approximately equal 60 percent of the GNP. According 
to the ministry, this rise was caused primarily by changes in 
currency exchange rates, that is, by the weakening of the markka 
against other currencies. The trade deficit actually increased 
the debt by only 5.5 billion markkas. 
  Now the net foreign debt is shrinking. The ministry is 
predicting a 16-billion-markka surplus in the balance of trade. 
  The Finance Ministry predicts that industrial investments 
will show a marked increase this year. This is explained by the 
fact that firms involved in exports will modernize their 
equipment and establish more production capacity. On domestic 
markets, investments will continue to decrease. 
  Investments by the public sector, that is primarily by the 
state and communities, will still decrease this year, according 
to the Finance Ministry. 
  The weak link in the entire national economy is consumer 
spending, which the Finance Ministry estimates will decrease 2.5 
percent this year. 
  The biggest decrease in consumer spending will be in goods 
and services related to foreign travel. This will decrease by 
more than one-tenth from last year's levels. 
  The Finance Ministry believes that the "change in the 
economic atmosphere" will cause people to cut back on savings 
this year. This will not, however, greatly increase consumer 
spending, since real disposable income for households will 
decrease further by 4 percent due to higher taxes. 
  According to the ministry, "the forecast for most service 
industries is continued difficult times, due to lethargic demand 
and weak profitability." According to the forecast, private 
sector services will still increase by 1 percent. 
All in all, the sum of the values of all produced goods and 
services, the GNP, will increase about 2 percent this year when 
compared to last year. Next year the GNP will increase by 5 
percent, according to the ministry's forecast. [passage omitted] 
  The rise in consumer prices, in other words, inflation, will 
continue to be very low in Finland. 
  Public-sector spending, as compared to the GNP, will 
decrease 
from more than 63 percent to 61 percent. This is partly due to 
the growth in the GNP, and another cause is the cuts in public 
sector spending. 


