<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Athens `Not Considering' Troop Dispatch to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2303170794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2303170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Greece is firm about implementing the general 
principles prevailing when UN peacekeeping forces are made up. 
Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos made his remarks when 
he was asked what Greece's stance would be following UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali's proposal to send 1,000 
Turkish blue helmets to Bosnia. 
  According to Venizelos, no formal decision has been made. He 
said Greece is optimistic and expects the criteria governing the 
composition of the peacekeeping forces will remain in force. 
  Venizelos pointed out that Turkey, in addition to its 
historic impediment in the region, has no legal right to 
participate in the UN peacekeeping forces, because of the 
Turkish occupation of Cyprus. 
  Asked if Greece has expressed any desire to participate in 
the UN force, the spokesman said: It is one thing to utilize 
particular procedural possibilities and participate in 
conferences, and it is another thing to insist on the firm 
criteria on the composition of the UN peacekeeping forces. 
Venizelos stressed that Greece is not considering the 
possibility of Greek blue helmets going to Bosnia and said that 
Greek foreign policy moves within the framework that was decided 
at the latest party leaders conference chaired by the president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

