<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Said Prepared To Sign FYROM Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2303192694 Athens ATHENS NEWS in English 22 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC2303192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ATHENS NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Greece has told the United Nations it is willing 
to sign a draft agreement with The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia [FYROM] and drop trade sanctions if the republic 
agrees to change its flag and amend its constitution, Mega 
Television News reported last night. Negotiations on the name, 
the report said, would be left to a later date. 
  Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias met President 
Konstandinos 
Karamanlis yesterday and told him he had notified UN mediator 
Cyrus Vance of Athens' position, Mega said. Earlier, the 
president received Miltiadhis Evert, the New Democracy leader. 
  After the talks, Mr. Papoulias said Greece was now waiting 
for mediator Vance to take the initiative. "We are waiting to 
see what Mr. Vance will do," Mr. Papoulias told reporters. 
"But, of course, in the meantime we will continue consultations 
with our European partners." 
  Mr. Papoulias added: "There was no reaction from the 
president either to the Skopje sanctions imposed by Athens last 
month, or to the government's diplomatic efforts since then." 
He thus denied conservative news headlines over the weekend, 
alleging a growing rift between the government of Andreas 
Papandreou and the presidency, as regards the former's handling 
of the FYROM problem. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos later also 
dismissed 
such reports as a "nonissue," because "our constitutional order 
functions perfectly, and the government spokesman is not 
entitled to elaborate or comment on the presidency's own 
announcements." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

