<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Criticizes UN in Somali Mission </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2303150494 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1406 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2303150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN)--The last soldiers of the German 
Somali contingent arrived at the military section of 
Cologne/Bonn airport today. Before German Defense Minister 
Volker Ruehe disbanded the unit, he praised the "masterly 
performance" of all those involved in the operation. The German 
armed forces had "opened up a new chapter in their readiness for 
deployment and aid." Ruehe stressed the soldiers' humanitarian 
aid, in particular. Schools, roads, and bridges had been 
rebuilt, and the infrastructure of the region had been 
considerably improved. He said the German soldiers had "turned 
the Beledweynne region into a model UN area for the rebuilding 
of Somalia." 
  Ruehe said the public supported such missions and expected 
them of the Bundeswehr. This acceptance would not, however, 
have been reached without its participation in Somalia and 
earlier in Cambodia, as well as in the aid flights to Bosnia and 
the AWACS missions. Ruehe, however, admitted to shortcomings in 
the Somalia mission, for which he primarily blamed the United 
Nations. He referred to the interaction between Mogadishu and 
New York, which was less than ideal, as well as the lack of a 
viable political concept for Somalia. Arising out of this is 
the task of strengthening the United Nations' ability to act. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

