<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Praises Bundeswehr Soldiers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403122294 Berlin DIE WELT in German 24 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["rmc"-signed report: "Somalia Mission Has Ended: Ruehe </F>
Praises the Bundeswehr"] 
  [Excerpt] Porz -- For Germany "Operation Somalia" has 
ended. With a military parade, Defense Minister Volker Ruehe 
(Christian Democratic Union) welcomed the last soldiers 
returning from the East African country at the Cologne/Bonn 
airport and officially dissolved the "Somalia Support Committee." 
  The minister praised the Bundeswehr for the skill it showed 
in the Somalia operation. He stressed the "masterly military 
achievements" of all those involved in supporting the UN blue 
helmet forces. "Punctually like a German Intercity train, the 
German contingents were are the disposal of the United Nations 
in Beledweynne," the minister stated, addressing 197 soldiers 
who had returned aboard a Bundeswehr plane from Djibouti a 
little while earlier. Ruehe particularly stressed the "excellent 
leadership" of the Somalia unit -- of Colonels Harf and 
Kammerhoff. He awarded them the Federal Service Cross on behalf 
of the federal president. 
  As clear as Ruehe's praise for his troops was his criticism 
of the shortcomings of the United Nations -- the main reason the 
German contingent was not able to supply a 4,500-men strong 
Indian brigade with water, foodstuffs, and other goods, as 
originally planned. Ruehe spoke of "quickly changing UN plans" 
and of an "apparently not optimal cooperation between Mogadishu 
and New York." He also pointed out that the United Nations had 
"no solid political concept" for the peace process in Somalia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

