<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Says Slovenia To Join Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2403121894 Paris AFP in English 1206 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2403121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 24 (AFP) -- The former Yugoslav 
republic of Slovenia will sign up to the Partnership for Peace 
programme of military cooperation with the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation Wednesday [30 March], a NATO official said Thursday. 
  Slovenia will become the first part of the former Yugoslavia 
to sign up to the NATO programme. Bosnia-Hercegovina and 
Croatia have also expressed interest in joining the Partnership, 
although no decision has been taken on it, the official said. 
  The Partnership for Peace programme allows for joint 
manoeuvres, military planning and peacekeeping operations with 
the existing NATO members. 
  NATO has already decided that four other countries can join 
the programme if they wish -- Austria, Finland, Sweden and 
Switzerland. 
  Russia is expected to sign up to the programme before the 
end 
of April. Georgia signed Wednesday, joining Albania, Bulgaria, 
the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, 
Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia and Ukraine. 
  Among the former Soviet republics, only Tajikistan has said 
it is not interested in joining the programme, the official 
added. 

</TEXT>

