<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Applicant Countries Seek To `Charm' EP </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2403175094 Oslo AFTENPOSTEN in Norwegian 22 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2403175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Oslo AFTENPOSTEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Norwegian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Morten Fyhn report: "Four Prime Ministers To Turn on the </F>
Charm"] 
  [Excerpt] Brussels -- Well aware that strong forces in the 
European Parliament [EP] -- the European Union's [EU] directly 
elected assembly -- are threatening to throw a monkey wrench in 
the works of the EU's plan to admit new members. Gro Harlem 
Brundtland and her fellow prime ministers from Sweden, Finland, 
and Austria have their sights set on a joint meeting with the 
Parliament's elected representatives. The meeting is expected 
to take place in Strasbourg on 19-20 April. 
  The timing of this obvious and unorthodox charm offensive on 
the part of the applicants has not been chosen by chance. For 
the meeting will take place immediately before the Parliament is 
timetabled to approve the outcome of membership negotiations on 
4 May and give the decisive go-ahead for EU enlargement. Some 
260 of the Parliament's 518 members must vote "yes" to new 
members. 
  The aim behind meeting the European Parliament deputies is 
to 
increase pressure on them so that they do not slow down EU 
enlargement. By their mere presence the applicant nations' 
prime ministers will also signal their interest -- not something 
which today's EU members lavish on the Parliament. 
  "A stroke of genius from the applicants," one source at the 
Parliament told AFTENPOSTEN. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

