<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Says Economic Recession Hits Bottom, Recovery Slow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303174494 Paris AFP in English 1657 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2303174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, March 23 (AFP) -- Economic recession in 
the European Community has probably touched bottom, but 
unemployment will keep climbing to a record high in 1995, EU 
Finance Commissioner Henning Christophersen said here Wednesday 
[23 March]. 
  In a report presented to the European Parliament, he 
predicted that recovery would be slow, with gross domestic 
product (GDP) inching up to an annual growth rate of 3 percent a 
year in 1996. 
  But Christophersen said there were no grounds for changing 
last November's estimate that GDP growth, after shrinking 0.3 
percent in 1993, would expand only weakly by 1.25 percent this 
year and 2 percent in 1995. 
  He said the unemployment rate -- 10.9 percent at the end of 
last year -- would reach a record 11.25 percent in 1995 before 
beginning to decline. 
  But the commissioner warned that the predictions were highly 
uncertain, and that recovery depended heavily on consumer 
confidence. 
  The EU's executive European Commission expects inflation -- 
3.4 percent last January -- to keep falling. 
  But it says efforts to cut government budget deficits -- 
essential for strong growth -- are being hindered by the glacial 
pace of recovery. 
  The report suggests that interest rates should be cut in 
order to fuel confidence and recovery, provided that inflation 
keeps falling. 
  It adds that even moderate economic growth is dependent on 
rising exports, investments and consumer confidence, along with 
continued pay moderation and government budget discipline. 
  Christophersen stressed the importance of steps to stimulate 
the economy, such as more research and training, plus 
implementation of an EU plan to spend massively on 
infrastructure transport, telecommunications and energy networks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19953 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu058cc_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-058 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

