<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU-Ukraine Sign Partnership Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2303161594 Brussels BELGA in Dutch 1408 GMT 23 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2303161594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed CET: "European Union Signs Partnership </F>
Agreement With Ukraine"; as released by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 23 Mar (BELGA) -- On Wednesday [23 March], 
the European Union (EU) and Ukraine signed a "partnership 
agreement." Ukraine is the first country belonging to the 
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) with which the EU has 
concluded such an agreement. 
  The partnership agreement could grow into a free trade zone 
between the EU and Ukraine. In 1998 both parties to the 
agreement will examine whether Ukraine has made sufficient 
progress in the direction of a market economy for negotiations 
on a free trade agreement to begin. 
  Our dream and our objective remains to join the EU, 
Ukrainian 
Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko said. Ukraine will launch its 
economic reforms as soon as possible. This year, 30,000 large 
and small companies will be privatized, Zlenko noted. 
  In the partnership agreement, both parties granted each 
other 
most favored nation status. That means that they will award 
each other all the trade benefits that they offer other 
countries. 
  The agreement provides for economic cooperation in highly 
divergent areas, such as industry, investment, public 
procurement contracts, scientific research, intellectual 
property, energy, the environment, transport, 
telecommunications, financial services, regional policy, and 
social cooperation. 
  In the introduction to the agreement it is expressly stated 
that democracy, human rights, and a market economy are the 
essential preconditions for cooperation. 
  The EU is negotiating a similar agreement with Russia. We 
are making good progress, but several problems still have to be 
ironed out, European Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan said . 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-19962 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu058__a94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-058-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 March 1994 </DATE1>

