<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Communique Criticizes Burundi Ethnic Violence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503121394 Brussels BELGA in French 1929 GMT 24 Mar 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2503121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed RAY: "Burundi -- European Union Blames </F>
Extremist Elements"; as released by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 24 Mar (BELGA) -- In a communique issued 
by the Twelve on Thursday [24 March], the European Union [EU] 
condemned ethnic violence in Burundi, blaming all extremist 
elements, whether government supporters, members of the 
opposition, or forces of order. 
  The EU communique stressed: "This violence endangers the 
institutional order in Burundi that has been patiently and 
courageously established by the democratic forces of the 
country." 
  The worsening of the situation in Bujumbura comes as the 
result of confrontation "between certain civil militia and the 
forces of order," the communique notes, adding that this 
violence had resulted in many victims "especially among the 
unarmed and innocent populations of the two ethnic groups." 
  The EU appealed to all sections of Burundi society, urging 
citizens to stop the violence and do everything necessary to 
ensure national reconciliation and to maintain the security of 
all Burundians in the democratic order. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

