<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Forecasts Economic Growth in East </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303132994 Hamburg DPA in German 1232 GMT 23 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2303132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Waren (DPA) -- In the view of Federal Economics 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt, the east German economy will grow by 6 
to 8 percent in 1994. There was a 7.1 percent increase last 
year. At the first industrial policy conference of Mecklenburg 
Western Pomerania in Klink, near Waren, Rexrodt said on 
Wednesday [23 March] that this land was one of the regions that 
was going through particularly profound structural changes. 
However, the upward trends were consolidating in the key 
industries of food, agriculture, and shipbuilding. 
  The Federal Government has so far supported this conversion 
with some 17 billion German marks [DM] in subsidies, which has 
helped to create or save a total of 445,000 jobs. According to 
Rexrodt, the Baltic Sea Highway A 20 will make the coastal 
region of Mecklenburg Western Pomerania more attractive to 
investors. 

</TEXT>

