<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Social Services Cost Over 1 Trillion Marks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203163394 Hamburg DPA in German 1311 GMT 22 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The overall expenditure on all the 
public and private social services was more than 1 trillion 
German marks [DM] in 1993 -- DM1,062 billion, to be exact. The 
share of this expenditure in GNP (social services quota) was 
approximately 34 percent. This is reported by the first 
all-German social report, which Labor Minister Norbert Bluem 
(Christian Democratic Union) presented to the Cabinet on Tuesday 
[22 March]. 
  The current increase in the burden of social insurance 
contributions is largely due to the expansion of social 
insurance to all of Germany that resulted from German 
unification, the report says. The transfer payments to eastern 
Germany corresponded to approximately 3 percent in contributions 
to west German social security. About DM118 billion from the 
coffers of pension and unemployment insurance went to the new 
laender between 1991 and 1993. 
  In western Germany the social services quota was 30.3 
percent 
in 1993; in the new laender, however, it was approximately 70 
percent. For 1997 the report predicts a decline in the 
all-German quota to 32 percent. 
  In western Germany the share of social expenditure in GNP 
declined from a record of 33.4 percent in 1981 to 28.9 percent 
in 1991. Most recently it has increased again because of 
improvements in the equalization of burdens for families and 
rising unemployment. In eastern Germany the quota reached its 
record so far in 1992 with 73.1 percent. The number of employed 
people in eastern Germany declined from about 9.9 million in 
1989 to only about 6.1 million in 1993. The number of 
registered unemployed was only 1.15 million in 1993. About 1 
million former GDR citizens have found jobs in western Germany, 
according to the report. 
  The Federal Government's social report has been presented 
irregularly since 1970. The previous report was published in 
June 1990 only for the old laender. At that time social 
expenditure of DM703 billion or 29.4 percent of GNP was 
predicted for all of 1990 in western Germany. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

