<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister: Posting Turks in Bosnia `Wrong' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2403191694 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2403191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias has stressed that 
our country insists on its firm position on the criteria 
governing the composition of the peacekeeping forces in Bosnia. 
Papoulias made his statement before leaving for Ioannina, where 
the European Union's General Affairs Council will meet on 26 
March. Kostas Papadhakis has the following report. 
  [Begin Papadhakis recording] Before leaving, Papoulias said 
that in addition to other topics, the Yugoslav and Bosnian 
issues will also be discussed at the meeting and that Greece 
will brief the delegates on its positions. No decisions will be 
made. The foreign minister described as an unpleasant 
development for the Turks the UN decision on the dispatch of 
Turkish blue helmets to Bosnia. He also noted that this 
decision was dictated by logistics without considering any 
historic foundations [katavoles] or psychology; instead of 
helping peace it might ultimately make things worse. 
  Referring to the Greek positions, Papoulias said that 
Greece's principle is that no blue helmets be sent to Bosnia. 
[end recording] 
  Papoulias described the UN Security Council's decision as 
wrong. 
  [Begin Papoulias recording] They made a mistake. We pointed 
this out. Often, I think, the historic foundation of problems 
is ignored and while we aim to satisfy the needs of logistics, 
we ignore a very significant element in human psychology, 
especially when it comes to the framework in which the Turkish 
troops will move in Bosnia. Instead of helping peace, I believe 
we are harming the peace process. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

