<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic `Hopeful' on Peace in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2403185194 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1530 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2403185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic is hopeful 
about the possibilities for peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
However, Granic does not believe that the Bosnian Serbs would 
want to join the federation negotiated by the Muslims and Croats 
on an equal basis. Granic also foresees difficulties in 
negotiations with the Serbs in Krajina. Antti Halinen reports. 
  [Begin recording] [Halinen] Granic, who was on a short visit 
to Helsinki, said that he is hopeful about the agreement on a 
federation signed by the Bosnian Muslims and Croats. 
  [Granic, in English] Concerning the future federation 
between 
the Muslims and Croats, I am optimist. 
  [Halinen] The situation there is better day by day. 
According 
to Granic, arrested people have been released, aid convoys can 
move again, and the confidence-building has started again. I 
think that the great majority of the Muslims and Croats supports 
the agreement, Granic says. 
  [Granic, in English] I think that very strong majority 
Muslims and Croats support it, the future federation. 
  [Halinen] Granic believes that the Bosnian Serbs will join 
the negotiations, but there are not many signs that they would 
join the agreement between the Muslims and Croats on an equal 
basis. [passage omitted] 
  According to Foreign Minister Granic, the first task is to 
create a lasting and universal cease-fire. According to Granic, 
the main problem in the negotiations with the Krajina Serbs is 
that they do not want autonomy but an independent state, and 
that is out of the question. 
  [Granic, in English] Definitely no state in the state, I 
told 
yesterday and two days ago... 
  [Halinen, interrupting] According to Granic, Croatia is 
prepared to grant the Krajina Serbs a local autonomy that is 
internationally monitored in two areas, but Croatia will not 
negotiate on regional integrity and sovereignty. Behind the 
unbending attitude of the Krajina Serbs is the support of Serbia 
and its president, Slobodan Milosevic, according to Granic. 
Granic says that more than 7,000 men and a lot of military 
equipment came from Serbia during last year to help the Serbs in 
Krajina. That is why it is not easy to find a solution in the 
negotiations without Belgrade's cooperation, Croatian Foreign 
Minister Mate Granic says. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

