<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jewish Leader Bubis Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2503111694 Hamburg DPA in German 0944 GMT 25 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2503111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DPA) -- "I am by no means surprised 
by this attack." On Friday [25 March], Ignatz Bubis, chairman 
of the Central Council of the Jews in Germany, reacted with 
these words to the arson attack on the synagogue in Luebeck. 
Such actions are not least due to the "mental arsonists" who 
create the climate for it with virulent campaigns and hate 
slogans, Bubis told DPA. For him, the real arsonists are 
extreme right parties, such as the Republikaner, the German 
People's Union, the National Democratic Party of Germany, and 
others of a total of 82 rightist groups and parties. 
  Bubis said that the fact that synagogues are targets of 
attacks by extreme right groups is new. In the past two years, 
Jewish graves and memorials were desecrated, but no synagogues. 
As a consequence of the incident in Luebeck, Bubis called for 
more severe social ostracism of "arsonists" and stricter 
punishment of the perpetrators. "Authorities and courts still 
have not understood that warnings and educational measures are 
not enough to deter right-wing extremists from such actions," 
the chairman of the Central Council said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

