<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rightist Accuses Bubis of Instigation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2603165094 Hamburg DPA in German 1554 GMT 26 Mar 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2603165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Erding (DPA) -- One day after the arson attack on 
the synagogue in Luebeck, Republikaner Chairman Franz 
Schoenhuber once again accused Ignatz Bubis, chairman of the 
Central Council of Jews in Germany, of "instigating people." He 
will not deviate "one centimeter" from this accusation, 
Schoenhuber said at a news conference at the Bavarian land 
congress of the right-wing extremist Republikaner in Erding near 
Munich on Saturday [26 March]. "The one who causes 
anti-Semitism in Germany is Mr. Bubis." 
  The delegates' meeting, from which the press was excluded, 
was accompanied by protests. "Right-wing extremists are once 
again waging war against a hesitating democracy," said Fritz 
Schoesser, Bavarian land chairman of the German Trade Union 
Federation, with a view to the latest attacks. At a peaceful 
memorial rally he stated that the 70,000 registered right-wing 
extremists are a "warning signal for democracy in this country." 
According to the police, about 600 people participated in the 
demonstration against right-wing extremism. 

</TEXT>

