<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Praises Somali Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503102494 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2108 GMT 24 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2503102494 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Somalia/Italy: Foreign Ministry on </F>
Reconciliation Accord"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Rome, March 24 -- The Italian foreign 
ministry on Thursday [24 March] expressed "appreciation" for the 
ceasefire and national reconciliation accord signed in Nairobi 
today by Somalia's two most powerful warlords, Mohamed Farah 
Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed. 
  In a communique, the ministry praised the mediating efforts 
of the special United Nations envoy and of neighboring countries 
and expressed the hope that the Nairobi accords "will facilitate 
the rapid re-establishment of conditions of greater trust and 
agreement" and "institutional solutions" that may keep Somalia 
united. 
  Italy will remain present in Somalia through its diplomatic 
seat and its development aid efforts and will take part in the 
country's reconstruction process, "as soon as conditions allow," 
said the ministry. 
  The agreement calls for "voluntary disarmament" and a 
national reconciliation conference in May to elect a president. 
It also repudiates all forms of violence as a means of 
resolving conflicts and calls for a meeting of Somali factions 
in Mogadishu on April 15 to set up rules and procedures for 
voting and criteria for participation in the reconciliation 
conference. 
  The reconciliation conference will allegedly elect a 
president, vice president and prime minister for Somalia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

