<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Condemns Berlusconi Allegation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503113394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1755 GMT 24 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2503113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ciampi Replies to Berlusconi on </F>
False Budget Charges"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, March 24 -- Prime Minister Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi on Thursday [24 March] broke his self-imposed 
silence for the March 27 election campaign and issued a stern 
reply to [Forza Italia leader] Silvio Berlusconi, the media 
magnate-turned-politician who last night accused the government 
of falsifying the state accounts. 
  "No one can honestly talk about falsifications," Ciampi said 
in a statement, referring to Berlusconi's allegations in a 
televised debate with Achille Occhetto, leader of the Democratic 
Party of the Left, that Budget Minister Luigi Spaventa had 
doctored the deficit figures. 
  Spaventa and Berlusconi will be facing off in Rome's 
downtown 
first-past-the-post constituency for a seat in the Senate. 
  "Last night the government was accused by a political 
candidate of having presented false budget figures, in contempt 
of parliament," Ciampi's statement said, adding: "In the face of 
this very grave affirmation I am forced to break the silence I 
had imposed on myself during this election campaign." 
  Ciampi also cited his decision not to take part in the 
campaign's closing forum, broadcast on public television Friday 
night and traditionally attended by the government chief. 
  In his statement, Ciampi reiterated that the cabinet's 
budget 
figures were compiled by the three finance ministers together, 
were approved by parliament and were in line with forecasts and 
calculations made by major international institutions. Upward 
revisions of the forecast 1994 deficit made earlier this week, 
he said, were in line with lower projected growth figures made 
by the same international organizations (European Union, OECD, 
IMF). 
  That part of the higher forecast deficit (14 trillion lire 
above the December forecasts) not caused by external economic 
factors amounts to some five trillion lire (3.1 billion 
dollars), Ciampi continued, but since revisions of this size, 
"considering payments of 700 trillion lire and revenues of 540 
trillion lire, happen in all countries, and no one can honestly 
talk about falsifications." 
  Ciampi then defended his government's economic policies, 
citing the renewed trust of foreign investors, successful 
privatizations and substantial interest rate cuts, which have 
reduced interests on debt servicing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

