<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe: `Some Progess' Made on FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2703135594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2703135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Intensive consultations are being held and movement 
toward resolving the The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia 
[FYROM] issue is being made at the ongoing informal meeting of 
the European Union [EU] foreign ministers in Ioannina. Late last 
night, French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said that progress 
was made on the FYROM issue. Today it was learned that EU 
Commissioner Hans Van Den Broek will visit Athens tomorrow for 
talks with Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias. Our Ioannina special correspondent 
Pavlos Tsoundos sent the following report a short time ago. 
  [Begin Tsoundos recording] There was intensive movement 
toward solution of the FYROM problem during the deliberations at 
the informal EU foreign ministers meeting, which is continuing 
and will conclude later today in Ioannina. 
  A short time ago, it was learned that Hans Van Den Broek, EU 
commissioner in charge of foreign policy, will discuss the issue 
in Athens tomorrow with Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and 
Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias. 
  At yesterday's meeting of the EU foreign ministers, the 
Greek 
presidency briefed its partners on the Greek countermeasures 
against FYROM and stressed the justified political character of 
the countermeasures. Mr. Papoulias stressed that the 
countermeasures are in agreement with EU law and are provided 
for by Article 224 of the EU Treaty. The exchange of views that 
followed were held in a friendly atmosphere and emphasis was 
given to role of the United Nations and mediator Cyrus Vance for 
a solution to the FYROM problem. In a statement late last 
night, French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said that some 
progress was made but did not commit himself to the possibility 
of a final solution in the current period. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

