<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows SPD Extending Lead Over CDU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703154194 Berlin DIE WELT in German 26 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2703154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Welt-Nachrichtendienst" report: "Political Barometer: </F>
SPD Extending Lead Over CDU"] 
  [Text] Berlin -- According to the March poll of the ZDF 
Political Barometer, the prospects for victory of the Social 
Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] have improved considerably in 
the voters' assessment. 
  According to the poll, 61 percent of Germans think that the 
SPD will win the Bundestag elections in October. In February 
this was the opinion of only 49 percent. Only 23 percent still 
think that the government coalition will win -- six percentage 
points less than a month before. According to the poll, 
approval for a potential red-green coalition at the federal 
level has also increased. It rose by 9 percentage points to 31 
percent most recently. 
  Another picture resulted from the question about voting 
behavior if elections were held next Sunday. The SPD got 39 
percent -- just as much as in February. The Christian 
Democratic Union/Christian Social Union lost 1 percentage point 
and went down to 36 percent. The Free Democratic Party of 
Germany remained unchanged at 6 percent and the Alliance 
90/Greens at 9 percent. The right-wing extremist Republikaner 
received 4 percent and the Party of Democratic Socialism, the 
successor of the Socialist Unity Party of Germany, 3 percent. 

</TEXT>

