<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur Claims Victory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2703200294 Paris AFP in English 1934 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2703200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, March 27 (AFP) -- Prime Minister Edouard 
Balladur claimed victory for his conservative coalition in local 
elections Sunday [27 March] and hinted that he would modify a 
controversial plan to lower the minimum wage for young people. 
  Speaking on television after polls closed in the 
second-round 
voting, Balladur said the French people had "confirmed the 
results of the first round" in which the two right-wing parties 
in his coalition won more than 44 percent of the votes. 
  Balladur thanked the French people for their support "all 
the 
more because these are difficult times" -- an allusion to a wave 
of student protests over the past two weeks against his youth 
employment plan. 
  Conceding that his proposals "are causing concern," Balladur 
said he would announce an initiative in the next few days "to 
reestablish dialogue." 
  "It is my responsibility and duty as head of the 
government," 
he added, "to respond to this appeal from our young people." 

</TEXT>

