<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Berlusconi Favors Scalfaro Remaining President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503135894 Rome LA REPUBBLICA in Italian 25 Mar 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR2503135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome LA REPUBBLICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Forza Italia leader Silvio Berlusconi by </F>
Franco Coppola in Rome on 24 March: "Berlusconi Trying To 
Conquer Presidency"] 
  [Excerpt] Rome -- [passage omitted] At 1400, among the 
stalls displaying drawings and trinkets, and surrounded by 
journalists and curious passers-by, Berlusconi announced that he 
considered President Oscar Scalfaro a fixed asset of the Second 
Republic. "As far as I am concerned, I see no reason why 
Scalfaro should not complete his term of office, in accordance 
with the provisions of the Constitution." Therefore, Scalfaro 
should stay on the Hill [president's palace] until 1999, the 
Knight [Berlusconi nickname] said. 
  [Coppola] So, in your opinion, Scalfaro is untouchable? 
However, your allies, [League Secretary] Umberto Bossi and 
Gianfranco Fini [leader of the Italian Social Movement, MSI] are 
saying, instead, that... 
  [Berlusconi] Please do not put words in my mouth. I never 
said "untouchable." I could never be so arrogant as to state or 
pronounce my opinion in those terms. I am only saying that the 
issue of the president of the republic has never been presented 
by the allies. 
  [Coppola] This may be so, but Bossi is saying the opposite, 
he is saying that Scalfaro should pack his bags. 
  [Berlusconi] By now Bossi is making it his profession to 
make 
statements against everything and everybody. 
  [Coppola] However, Fini is also saying that the president 
will have to step down. 
  [Berlusconi] I believe this is not the right moment to 
address this issue. I have expressed my opinion. We will see 
what happens later. They have never taken up this issue with 
me. I believe it ought to be discussed at the right moment. We 
must first see how Italians vote, see the actual figures. 
  [Coppola] Some people are suggesting that a change is taking 
place in the "institutional" political scene -- namely, that you 
are undermining the agreement between the PDS [Democratic Part 
of the Left] and Scalfaro. 
  [Berlusconi] I do not believe you can speak of alliances as 
far as the president of the republic is concerned, because the 
head of state must be above the opposing sides. I believe that 
Scalfaro is very much aware of this rule, and that he is fully 
observing it. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

