<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-059 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fishermen Compensated in Swedish EU Deal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2503164294 Copenhagen DET FRI AKTUELT in Danish 23 Mar 94 
p 12 </F>

<F P=103> PM2503164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen DET FRI AKTUELT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [RITZAUS BUREAU report: "Extra Fish for Bornholm"] </F>
  [Text] Brussels -- Bornholm's fishermen yesterday received 
compensation for the fish catches they would have lost as the 
result of a "technical error" during the negotiations on Swedish 
membership of the European Union [EU]. 
  It would seem that it was the Greek presidency that, in the 
nocturnal negotiations with Sweden earlier this month, made the 
mistake by forgetting to consult Denmark before Sweden was 
allowed to increase its cod quota in the Baltic Sea from 35 to 
40 percent. 
  Danish diplomatic circles reject the notion that the error 
could be on the Danish side. The Danes saw no document that 
quoted the figure of 40 percent, and they had therefore only 
approved an offer of 35 percent, the diplomats say. 
  The result of yesterday's discussions in the Council of 
Ministers was that the Council has committed itself to buying 
fishing rights in the Baltic from other countries -- the Baltic 
countries and Russia, for example -- corresponding to what has 
been lost by Bornholm's fishermen because of the concessions to 
Sweden. 
  "With this agreement we have protected Bornholm's 
fishermen's 
interests, and I view this as an important result," Foreign 
Minister Niels Helveg Petersen (Radical Liberal Party) said 
yesterday evening. "An error had unfortunately occurred, and I 
do not know precisely how this happened." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

