<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aho: EU Vote Possible on Same Day as Sweden </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2503162094 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 24 Mar 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PM2503162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Bjarne Nitovuori report: "EU Referendum To Be Held in </F>
November?"] 
  [Excerpt] The referendum on Finland's EU [European Union] 
membership could be arranged for 13 November, Father's Day -- 
the same day that Sweden is arranging its referendum. 
  This idea surfaced in an interview with Prime Minister Esko 
Aho (Center Party) in Center Party newspaper LALLI yesterday. 
  It was not Aho but the interviewer who brought up the idea, 
and Aho replied that this is an alternative that has not been 
ruled out. 
  "I have argued for an earlier date. Here I have been 
thinking chiefly about September, but now the delay with the 
decisions means that serious consideration is also being given 
to a later date." 
  However, according to Aho, 13 November is the latest 
possible 
date, otherwise we will be much too close to the Eduskunta 
election. This takes place in March next year. 
  Aho also thinks that a shared referendum day for Finland and 
Sweden -- "and why not Norway too" -- would underline the fact 
that the Nordic countries are in the same position and their 
decisions are interdependent. 
  According to Aho, this would also have the positive effect 
of 
ruling out the domino effect -- so that the referendum result in 
one country will not influence public opinion in another where 
the referendum is held at a later date. 
  Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto (Center Party) yesterday 
told agricultural journalists that he would prefer a referendum 
after the Swedish poll -- that is, after a date which, according 
to Aho, is the "last possible date." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

