<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Commissioner Concludes Visit, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2503163294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1500 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2503163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] EU [European Union] Commissioner on Foreign Affairs 
Hans Van Den Broek said that during his visit to Cyprus he 
reconfirmed his impression of the last few months about the 
Cyprus Government's firm belief in the effort to achieve a 
peaceful solution to the Cyprus issue, as well as its effort to 
harmonize, in any way, its economic and trade policy with the 
European Union's policy. Speaking at Larnaca Airport shortly 
before his departure for Athens, Van Den Broek again expressed 
the European Union's multiple support for the 
confidence-building measures, which he said are an important 
step toward the achievement of an overall solution to the Cyprus 
issue. The EU commissioner added that he has assured both 
President Glavkos Kliridhis and Foreign Minister Alekos 
Mikhailidhis that in case the confidence-building measures are 
implemented, the European Union is ready to offer any help and 
the EU commission will proceed in that direction with the 
presentation of proposals to the EU Council of Ministers. 
  Foreign Minister Mikhailidhis said that Cyprus' movement 
toward Europe has began and will end with its accession to the 
European Union. Speaking at Larnaca Airport shortly before Van 
Den Broek's departure, the foreign minister stressed that Cyprus 
is working hard for its accession and has already proceeded with 
a series of decisions in this direction. Mikhailidhis said that 
the harmonization of Cypriot legislation with that of the 
European Union continues at a quick pace. He added that Cyprus' 
foreign policy will also begin to be in line with that of the 
European Union. Referring to the talks he had with EU 
Commissioner Van Den Broek, the Cypriot foreign minister 
described them as constructive and comprehensive. 

</TEXT>

