<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kliridhis Views Current Developments on CBM's </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2703143094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2703143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis said that Cyprus has 
taken the initiative for the first time by promoting Cyprus' 
accession to the European Union [EU], the unified Greece-Cyprus 
defense doctrine, and the Greek Cypriot side's irreproachable 
stand at the proximity talks. On the contrary, he added, Turkey 
and Rauf Denktas are struggling to escape from the suffocating 
encirclement being created around them. 
  In an address at the Lions Club in Paralimni, President 
Kliridhis noted that the Turkish side now opposes the 
suggestions by the UN Secretary General and his representatives 
for the implementation of the confidence-building measures 
[CBM's] on Famagusta. He further said that in January 1995 
Cyprus will open talks with the EU for accession to it whether 
or not there is progress in the Cyprus issue because of Turkish 
intransigence. He also noted that the accession talks will 
concern the whole of the Republic of Cyprus. President 
Kliridhis is heading for accession to the EU. He added: The 
road to accession has opened because the Greek Cypriot side's 
behavior toward the CBM's has been irreproachable; this is 
affirmed by the five permanent members of the Security Council. 
  Mr. Kliridhis said that at the proximity talks the Turkish 
side did not accept the UN suggestion that the Famagusta area 
between the sea and Dherinia, including the road, be abandoned 
by Turkish troops and placed under UN control so that there will 
be safe access to and from Famagusta. He added that the Turks 
did not accept UN administration of the town and demanded a 
trilateral administration with the participation of Greek 
Cypriots, Turkish Cypriots, and some presence of the 
international organization. Mr. Kliridhis further noted that 
the Turks also did not accept the schedule for handing over the 
town or a series of other UN suggestions. 

</TEXT>

