<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton's Letter to Papandreou `Constructive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2603131994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2603131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. President Bill Clinton has sent a letter to 
Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, asking for the earliest 
possible settlement of the issues pending between Athens and 
Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM]. Mr. 
Clinton pointed out that a solution that is fair to both sides 
can be found. Referring to the Cyprus issue, the U.S. President 
expressed his intention to have personal contacts with both 
interested parties, particularly with regard to the 
confidence-building measures. 
  Responding to a question from journalists on President Bill 
Clinton's letter to Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, 
Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos made the following 
statement: President Clinton's letter to Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou was been sent in connection with the upcoming visit 
by Mr. Andreas Papandreou to the United States and refers 
concisely to all the issues that will be discussed. It is a 
friendly and constructive letter that constitutes a serious 
basis for discussion, given the U.S. intentions to address all 
the problems and de-escalate tensions. 
  Answering another relevant question, the Government 
spokesman 
made it clear that the question of Turkish troops being sent to 
Bosnia is not raised in the letter, while on the Skopje issue 
President Clinton outlined the well-known U.S. positions, which 
have also been expressed publicly. 

</TEXT>

