<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Foreign Ministers Meet To Discuss Enlargement, FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2603183194 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1700 
GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2603183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Foivos Karzis in Ioannina] </F>
  [Excerpts] The EU [European Union] foreign ministers' 
unofficial meeting began with some delay. The Yugoslav crisis 
and the EU's enlargement are at the center of discussions. 
According to reports, on the Yugoslav issue, the ministers 
examined the possibility of appointing a special commissioner 
for the area of Mostar. 
  The 12 ministers also discussed the issue of The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] and Greece's 
countermeasures. The Greek side stressed that the issue is 
primarily political and time should be allowed so ongoing 
mediation efforts produce results. In the framework of the 
discussion, the ministers discussed the recent letter by [FYROM 
President] Kiro Gligorov to EU Commission President Jacques 
Delors. [passage omitted] 
  The foreign ministers of many countries also referred to the 
issue of Skopje as they arrived in Ioannina, and it appears that 
our partners now recognize the political aspect of the issue 
even though they continue supporting the lifting of Greece's 
countermeasures. [passage omitted] 
  The issue of the EU's enlargement caused the first change to 
the meeting's agenda. It is a change that could prove important 
in its own particular way. 
  [Begin correspondent Simos Kedhikoglou recording] Despite 
procedural difficulties, the issue of the EU's enlargement will 
be at the center of the 12 ministers' discussions. A working 
group has already been set up to examine all the parameters of 
the problem. In addition, Alternate Foreign Minister Theodhoros 
Pangalos is having bilateral contacts with his counterparts. At 
the same time, the Greek presidency will present its own 
proposal with the support of the EU Commission and its 
president, Delors, in an attempt to seek a mutually acceptable 
solution. Indicative of the importance of the issue of the EU's 
enlargement are the remarks of the foreign ministers during 
their arrival at Ioannina, where they did not refrain from 
straightforward attacks against the countries that oppose the 
enlargement, mainly Britain. EU Commission President Delors was 
more reserved than all the others as he limited himself to a 
meaningful hand gesture. The general spirit is one of reserved 
optimism that the problem will be solved but there is an 
understanding of the difficulties. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

