<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Terrorist' Carlos, Weinrich Reported in Damascus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2603095294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0336 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2603095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DDP/ADN) -- According to information from 
the Federal Office of Criminal Investigations and the Berlin 
police, top terrorist Carlos and his German accomplice Johannes 
Weinrich are still in Syria. Eyewitness reports say the two men 
are already well-known among German businessmen and German 
Embassy staff in Damascus, the news magazine DER SPIEGEL reports 
in its latest edition. 
  Carlos and Weinrich are alleged, among other things, to have 
been responsible for the bomb attack on the French Cultural 
Center in Berlin in August 1983, in which one person died. The 
German Government requested the extradition of the two 
terrorists from the Syrian Government in October 1992. 
  Recent questioning of returning German businessmen indicated 
that Weinrich was still openly moving around the Syrian capital 
in July 1993. The security authorities assume that Carlos and 
Weinrich are still in Damascus, SPIEGEL adds. However, this has 
been denied by Syrian Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' to his 
German counterpart Klaus Kinkel last week, the magazine writes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

