<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Justice Minister Visits, Holds Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views Rights With Counterpart </H4>
<F P=102> LD2803143594 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1225 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Justice Minister Sabine 
Leutheusser-Schnarrenberger (FDP) has called for "clear signals" 
from the Chinese Government of a change in its human rights 
situation. The human rights issue was of great significance in 
Sino-German relations, the minister said after talks with her 
Chinese counterpart, Yang Xiao, in Bonn today. A "basic 
agreement" on human rights is indispensable to cooperation with 
Beijing. 
  Germany and China joined international agreements based on 
the universal applicability and indivisibility of human rights, 
the minister stressed. The interstate dialogue on human rights 
became a component of international law after the World War II. 
Thus, a dialogue of this kind is not inadmissible interference 
in a country's internal affairs. Bonn does indeed recognize the 
significance of "national and regional distinctive features as 
well as different historical, cultural, and religious 
prerequisites." However, "basic human rights criteria" are valid 
everywhere. 
  In the "very open" dialogue with the Chinese politician she 
stressed the human rights of the individual. China, on the 
other hand, has focused on "collective human rights." It is 
important that these different views be discussed openly. 
However, it would be "very desirable" if agreement could be 
reached on the "basic human rights criteria." [passage omitted] 
  Yang Xiao stressed that they were able to achieve a 
consensus 
on many issues. However, given the differences in social order 
and economic development and the different cultural 
prerequisites, it is obvious that they would also have differing 
views. Nevertheless, his country is ready to enter a dialogue 
"based on equality." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

